import java.util.Scanner;

public class Calculator {
public static void main(String[] args) {
Scanner input = new Scanner(System.in);

System.out.println("Welcome to the Basic Calculator!");
System.out.print("Enter the first number: ");
double num1 = input.nextDouble();

System.out.print("Enter the operator (+, -, *, /): ");
char operator = input.next().charAt(0);

System.out.print("Enter the second number: ");
double num2 = input.nextDouble();

double result;

switch (operator) {
case '+':
result = num1 + num2;
System.out.println("Result: " + result);
break;
case '-':
result = num1 - num2;
System.out.println("Result: " + result);
break;
case '*':
result = num1 * num2;
System.out.println("Result: " + result);
break;
case '/':
if (num2 == 0) {
System.out.println("Error: Division by zero is not allowed.");
} else {
result = num1 / num2;
System.out.println("Result: " + result);
}
break;
default:
System.out.println("Error: Invalid operator");
}

input.close();
}
}

author: @anuragrai8283
comment_text:
14:57 for anybody wondering(and this is why I think it is):-

1 byte = 8 bits

Let this(8 box pack) represent a "byte" where each box denotes a "bit"(binary digit aka 0 or 1)
‚ñ¢‚ñ¢‚ñ¢‚ñ¢‚ñ¢‚ñ¢‚ñ¢‚ñ¢

Now, if we use the first box to store the sign of the number(+ve, -ve), we`re left with 7 boxes to represent a decimal number in binary representation using 0s and 1s
The total number of individual ways in which we can arrange 0s and 1s in the 7 boxes to form a unique number OR the total number of possible decimal numbers we can represent is-

2^7 (2x2x2x2x2x2x2) <2 coz binary digits are just 2 ie 0 and 1 and we have two options to fill each of the seven boxes>

2^7 = 128
and with the one box we left for holding the sign, we can basically store 128 negative numbers(-1 to -128) and 128 positive numbers(0 to 127)
[0 can have any sign in ordinary mathematics so whatever] and if you`re really wondering about it-
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/33159303/in-signed-primitives-is-0-positive-or-negative-or-both

PS- Don`t come after me for having explained a silly thing üíÄ

Java Statement Types.


Type of statements in java

In Java, there are several types of statements that can be used to perform different operations. Some of the most common types of statements in Java include:

Expression Statements: These statements are used to evaluate an expression and can include method calls, assignments, and other operations.

Declaration Statements: These statements are used to declare a new variable or constant and specify its type.

Control Flow Statements: These statements are used to control the flow of execution in a program, including if-else statements, switch statements, loops (for, while, do-while), and try-catch statements.

Jump Statements: These statements allow the program to jump to a specific part of the code, including break, continue, and return statements.

Assertion Statements: These statements are used to check assumptions made by the programmer and throw an error if the assertion fails.

Synchronized Statements: These statements are used to control access to shared resources in a multithreaded environment.

Labeled Statements: These statements are used to provide a label to a block of code, which can be used for easy navigation and readability.

Block Statements: These statements are used to group a set of statements together, which can be treated as a single unit for control flow or variable scoping.

comment_text:
Generalized formula: -
Firstly consider the how many bytes that particular data type takes, suppose taking 'int' as an example, it take 4 bytes which is equals to
(8*4 = 32 bits) [1 byte = 8 bit] so the generalized formula will be [-2^n/2 to 2^n/2 -1], here n is the number of bits.....
Considering our example of int data type the generalized formula will be [-2^32/2 to 2^32-1] on further calculation it will be ranging between
[-2147483648 to 2147483647].
Hope it helps :D

18:06 void getRange(string type, int n) {
if(type.compare("SIGNED") == 0) { //for signed numbers calculate lower and upper limit
int min = pow(2, n - 1);
int max = pow(2, n - 1) - 1;
cout << "Range from " << (-1) * min << " to " << max <<endl;
}else{ //for signed numbers calculate limit from 0
int range = pow(2, n )-1;
cout << "Range from 0 to " << range << endl;
}
}

comment_text:
Range of a data type that takes 'n' bytes of space would be : - (2^ n*8)/2 to +[(2^ n*8)/2] -1
total space it occupies : n bytes
total bits it can hold : n*8 bits
total values would be : 2^ (n*8)
so, range would be : [-2^ (n*8)]/2 to [+2^ (n*8)]/2 -1

// Input any primitive data type byte value and get its range value:

import java.util.Scanner;

public class App {
public static void main(String[] args) {
Scanner numScanner = new Scanner(System.in);
byte byteNum = 8;
System.out.print("Enter the primitive data type byte value: ");
int valueRange = numScanner.nextInt() * byteNum;
long algo1 = (Math.round(Math.pow(valueRange, 2)) / 2);
long algo2 = (Math.round(Math.pow(valueRange, 2)) / 2);

System.out.println("Value ranges from: -" + algo1 + " to " + (algo2 - 1));
}
}

-(2^(n*8))/2 to ((2^(n*8))/2)-1

//package is like the name of code
public class Main {

//public is for use this code in anywhere
//function is called under class
public static void main(String[] args) {
// at first lets write a hello world program
System.out.println("Hello World with Fokir");
// This Code is for learn Variable
System.out.println("We Have two type's of variable primitive and non-primitive ");
//if you know your value of variable than use specific variable which is in your value range
// because it will make your program faster and small size
byte b=100;
short s= 1000;
int i=10000;
long l=100000L;
//i use String.format for print everything under one print function
System.out.println(String.format("There We Are Showing Int's 4 Type of Primitive variable " +
"Byte is 1 byte and range is -128 to 127 and variable value is= %s " +
"Short is 2 byte and its range is ‚àí32768 to 32767 and variable i give is= %s " +
"Int is 4 byte and its range is ‚àí2147483648 to 2147483647and variable i give is=%s " +
"Long Is 8 byte and its range is 9223372036854775808 to 9223372036854755807 and variable i give is=%s ",b,s,i,l));
System.out.println("Now we are going to see Our Others Four Type of variable's ");
// if you want you can right these variable at first but i write them in here for my Advantages
float f=1.0000007F;
//use floate if your value is under 7 digit's after the dot(.) if value is more, than use double
double d=9.9969769697;
boolean bool=false;
char c='A';
//here we will use multiple print function to show you how to write multiple print function for program
//but my personal recommendation is write in one function it will space cutting and faster for software

System.out.println("Float is 4 byte and range is¬±3.40282347E+38F and (6-7 significant decimal digits) the value i give is= "+f);
System.out.println("Double is 8 byte and range is4.94065645841246544e-324d to 1.79769313486231570e+308d (positive or negative)" +
" the value i give is= "+d);
System.out.println("Boolean is 1 bit and it Stores true or false values, the value i give is= "+bool);
System.out.println("Char is 2 byte and the value i give is="+c);

// our variable description's and print function is well explained above now we are going to write sum code

System.out.println(" Now we are going to see a sum of two variable lets take first int and float");
// the value is same as for the sum
double sum=i+f;

System.out.println(sum);
// I dont use (" ") to make sum print in the print function its a rule for print
}
}
